post_text:
PSA for all soon-to-be kindergarten mamas...
Practice eating “school lunch” with your kiddo. Make sure they can open everything you send with them. Talk about not eating off of the table in the lunchroom!!! Set a timer for 15 minutes and talk about how they may not finish eating and that’s ok. (This was HARD for little man.) Practice packing everything back up and talk about what is trash and what should come back home in their lunch box. Kindergarten lunch is a big adjustment and your child’s teacher will be super appreciative if you have prepared them for the experience!

Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) is a one-time food benefit for families who lost access to free or reduced-price meals due to school closures. Eligible P-EBT families will receive application instructions from schools in late May. The P-EBT application will open the first week of June.

P-EBT food benefits are for children who received SNAP food benefits for March 2020 and children who are certified for free or reduced-price school meals during the 2019-20 Texas school year. For more information, visit: hhs.texas.gov/PEBT

Cross Roads FFA / Cross Roads Young Farmers
May 22 at 8:31 AM ·

Today is the day, GRADUATION DAY!!! It has been a great ride with all of our senior CRFFA members. We are going to miss you all. Please remember the FFA motto. Doing to learn, Learning to do, Earning to live, and LIVING TO SERVE!!

You are always welcome to drop in at the Ag Building to visit, for a little free advise, or to share your newest accomplishments.

Please take a moment to enjoy our CRFFA 2019-2020 President, Trent Watson, as he gives his retiring address.

Thank you so much for support our students.

post_text:
Cross Roads High School has a senior tradition of hosting "Honors Night Out". This is a special banquet that honors the top 10 seniors in the class. Each senior invites a teacher (past or present) that has impacted them during their education here at Cross Roads. During the banquet, the student and teacher have the opportunity to speak about one another. With all that has gone on, our seniors did not get to have this opportunity. So we felt that we could do this a little different.
We would like to give all the teachers, coaches, employees and administrators the opportunity to address these students and share a memory of them, or what stood out about them, or just good wishes to these seniors. So if you taught one or all of these special kiddos, please feel free to comment on their photo. I know I look forward to reading each one of them.

post_text:
Congratulations to Cross Roads High School Class of 2020 Valedictorian, Hannah Nicole Latham. Hannah is the daughter of April and Brian Latham. While in high school Hannah was the captain of the varsity volleyball team, softball team, track, cross country, golf, and cheerleading teams and earned many district and county honors. She was also a member of the National Honor Society, Student Council,a class officer and has completed her Associates Degree from Trinity Valley Community College.
Upon graduation, Hannah plans to attend the University of Texas in Tyler to obtain her Master's in Nursing to become a nurse practitioner. Congratulations Hannah and good luck in the future.
text:
Congratulations to Cross Roads High School Class of 2020 Valedictorian, Hannah Nicole Latham. Hannah is the daughter of April and Brian Latham. While in high school Hannah was the captain of the varsity volleyball team, softball team, track, cross country, golf, and cheerleading teams and earned many district and county honors. She was also a member of the National Honor Society, Student Council,a class officer and has completed her Associates Degree from Trinity Valley Community College.
Upon graduation, Hannah plans to attend the University of Texas in Tyler to obtain her Master's in Nursing to become a nurse practitioner. Congratulations Hannah and good luck in the future.

post_text:
Congratulations to Cross Roads High School Salutatorian, Preston Turner. Preston is the grandson of Susan and Robert Tans. While in high school, Preston was involved in marching band, football, cross country, and track. Preston also competed in UIL Speech and Debate, one act play, and UIL academics. He was a member of the National Honor Society and FCCLA. Preston was a regular blood donor for Carter Blood Care and volunteered his service to Faith in Action and the Shady Oaks Baptist Church.
Preston plans on attending the University of Texas in Tyler to obtain his Bachelors degree in Computer Engineering.

Questions have come in on how we are creating packets with specific concerns about the possible spread of germs. Please know that we are following every CDC guideline when creating packet materials and stuffing the packets. Materials sit in the open, untouched for 3 days before being put into the packets. The packets are then sealed and sit untouched for 4 days prior to being passed out to parents.

Please be assured that we are doing everything in our power to keep you and your families safe while continuing to educate your children during this unprecedented time. If you have any questions or concerns do not hesitate to reach out!

Parents, Students and Community members:
Keeping you safe and educated is always our top priority, so we’d like to share some important facts about the coronavirus. Together we can slow the spread just by staying at home! If you must go out, stay at least 6 feet away from others, and disinfect frequently touched surfaces like countertops and doorknobs whenever you return.
Keep germs away by washing your hands with soap and water for 20 seconds. To keep from spreading germs, avoid touching your eyes, nose, or mouth and cover a cough or sneeze with your elbow. If you have symptoms of COVID-19 – a fever, dry cough, or shortness of breath – call your doctor. We hope to see you all very soon!

Parents and Students,

UPDATED MARCH 31ST @ 2:30PM
Cross Roads ISD will be closed through May 4th .

Home learning packets are due April 6th and must be completed. You can turn them in during your meal delivery, meal pick-up, or dropped off at your campus office.

New packets will also go out on April 6th and will be due back each Monday thereafter. Pick-up will be between 9:00 am to 11:00 am and 5:00 pm to 7:00 pm each Monday for the remainder of weeks that the school is closed.
Future announcements on closure will be make weekly or as per government announcement. Please watch our Facebook page and website for any updates.

Feel Free to contact the teachers through email concerning the packet instructional materials and Food Services referring to student breakfast and lunch needs at 903-489-1530.

text:
Parents and Students,

UPDATED MARCH 31ST @ 2:30PM
Cross Roads ISD will be closed through May 4th .

Home learning packets are due April 6th and must be completed. You can turn them in during your meal delivery, meal pick-up, or dropped off at your campus office.

New packets will also go out on April 6th and will be due back each Monday thereafter. Pick-up will be between 9:00 am to 11:00 am and 5:00 pm to 7:00 pm each Monday for the remainder of weeks that the school is closed.
Future announcements on closure will be make weekly or as per government announcement. Please watch our Facebook page and website for any updates.

Feel Free to contact the teachers through email concerning the packet instructional materials and Food Services referring to student breakfast and lunch needs at 903-489-1530.

Please be patient and understanding as information is changing rapidly with more directives from state agencies.

Thank you for your cooperation and understanding.

March 17 at 7:52 PM ·

UPDATE FROM HCLS OFFICIALS———

Mr. Tappan and Mr. Choate will be contacting everyone tomorrow regarding how you would like your animals processed, floored, or if you have other plans for your project.

Our drop off if you want to floor or process your animals is Saturday the 28th at 11am. Only processors available are J&S and Columbia.

We have to get the forms filled out and delivered back to their office by 10am this Friday 3/20/20.

Everyone who validated an animal will receive a premium check. Yet to be determined a value.

They refunded all breeding, shop, horse, entry fees to the chapter.

Commercial heifers can still be sold at the sale barn on the 27th must be there by 10am on that Friday. If the sale is open.

All money will be collected by HCLS, put into one account, and distributed by them.

There will be no add-ons collected by HCLS and distributed to individual exhibitors.

As many of you have heard the very sad news, Coach Curtis Corley passed away yesterday, February 10th. He was a wonderful Coach and a dear friend and mentor to everyone in Cross Roads. He will be truly missed each and every day. Please keep Mrs. Corley, Brooke and their family in your thoughts and prayers in these most difficult days to come.
The funeral arrangements are being made at the Carrol-Lehr funeral home in Athens. There will be a visitation from 6-8 on Thursday, February 13th at Rock Hill Baptist Church in Brownsboro and the service will be held the following day at 1:00 at Rock Hill Baptist Church.
Here are a couple of photos of Coach Corley this season coaching kids and making a real difference in each of their lives.

post_text: Athletes and Parents, the UIL has released a public report that has led to some questions. The report says that we will not be playing football next year. We are letting you know that we will be playing football at both the Jr. High and High School levels. We will have the ability to play JV and Varsity teams the next 2 seasons. We are doing this to hopefully raise the number of athletes competing in football and to build our program to level that our athletes, coaching staff, administration, and community would like it to be. Furthermore, our band, cheerleaders, will still be involved in all football related activities. All other UIL events will be unchanged. The coaching staff will hold a meeting with athletes on Wednesday for further communication. Thank you CRISD Coaches.

shared_text:
Alex Montgomery‎Cross Roads Band Booster
December 5, 2019 at 11:17 PM ·

Soooooooo proud of these 7th and 8th grade students for competing today in the Middle School All-Region auditions! We've made miles of improvement from last year, and were great representatives of our Cross Roads Bobcat Band! Unlike last year, we had two students make the cut! Donna Stovall and Natalie Giles earned the privilege of representing Cross Roads again this coming Janurary as they rehearse and perform an entire concert in just TWO DAYS!! These ladies earned their spots in the band against over 60 other Trumpet players. WOW! 😲
Natalie placed 9th in the Region Symphonic Band and Donna placed 8th in the Region Concert Band. This is such an honor that was only achieved by an immense amount of hard work, and dedication. Again, I encourage ALL students to audition, and keep auditioning year after year.

P.S.- Special shoutout to my AWESOME High School students who cleaned up my podium while I was out today! Y'all the real mvps ✊✊

Texas Farm Bureau
December 4, 2019 at 8:25 AM ·

Meet Braden and Jordan McInnis. They grow corn, wheat, cotton, soybeans, grain sorghum, oats and hay and raise cattle in Anderson County. Braden, a first-generation farmer, began farming in high school and continues to expand his operation. They also custom farm and recently started clearing timber. Jordan is the lead agricultural science teacher and FFA advisor at Elkhart High School. They’re finalists in this year’s TFB Outstanding Young Farmer & Rancher competition.

Remember: Thanksgiving Feast is tomorrow,Friday, November 22nd. Parents are invited to eat with their children during lunch. All guests and parents will need to enter the building at the Elementary office. Parents, please park in the front of the school in the parking areas and please refrain from parking in the grass, ditches or on the sides of the highway. There is additional parking behind the cafeteria (the old gym parking) and the Event Center parking lot is also available. Please do not block any vehicles as the lunch times are different for each grade level and people will be coming and going all day.
Teachers please remember to park in the high school faculty parking or in the Event center parking. High school students will be parking in the home football parking area. Have a great Day and thank you in advance for your cooperation.

October 9, 2019 at 4:30 PM ·

The Athens High School Student Council hosted 232 students representing 17 area schools today, as part of the District 4 Student Council Fall Conference. The diverse group discussed how to advance this year’s state project, which focuses on poverty awareness. AHS Student Council officers are President Joel Vasquez, Vice President Isabel Gonzalez, Secretary Jesica Cleto, Treasurer Sydney Briggs, Parliamentarian Jasmin Lora and Reporter Aspen Odum. They are sponsored by Julie Hill. Great job, Hornets!

post_text:
CRHS FCCLA Officers Traveled to Denton this weekend to Participate in Peer Education.
Peer Education is a concept developed by National FCCLA to develop programs which are delivered to their membership and members' communities via their members - hence the term peer education.
Peer education is a great place for members to begin if they want to become involved! Members have the opportunity to identify a concern in their community in relationship to one of the peer education areas, set a goal, plan a series of three projects, carry their projects out, reflect on their project, submit their projects to state staff and State Executive Council for review, and last but not least, receive recognition for the work they have accomplished.
